Art;<br><br>
Your post brought back from memories, from Nam and some time ago.<br>
I was not religious in Vietnam, I figured if I went to church, Catholic or Protestant, it made no difference who was preaching. I figured if I went God sort of owed me one. If He got me out of a tight situation, I owed Him one. I would go to the services provided if we were not on gate watch or out on patrol. <br>
I am not to sure if we weren't ordered to go. Why with the padre or chaplain coming out, I believe the lieutenant or some higher up required us to go so as the Priest would have an audience. <br>
Funny though, now thinking about it, it was always the guys in the rear, as well as from Arty or mortars that went the most. Now, I don't know if they were more sinners then us grunts, or it may have been that they had more time to think about life and death and religious sort of things.<br>
I do remember some powerful prayers I uttered, promising the God of Abraham and Jacob that if he got me out of the situation I may have been in at that time, that I would go to church every Sunday, Why I would go twice on Sunday, I often prayed. But, when I returned stateside of course, I never went.<br><br>
Art, Several years ago, I was bothered with a concern similar to the one you have stated above and as one thought led to another, with a sincere heart, I asked God if there was a hell. It was that sort of silent prayer we often uttered as the choppers descended into a HOT LZ. I really wanted to know.<br><br>
Only silence followed, like the silent prayers many wrote on helmet covers, <br>
&quot;Just you and Me, Right Lord.&quot;<br>
I often wondered if the Marine meant it as a joke, a sincere prayer or if he was asking for re-assurance from above.<br><br>
Weeks after my request, I had a dream, a vision in the night, but very real, a dream I have never forgotten. In a dream that seemed more like a vision, more as if I was awake then asleep, the hand of God picked me up. A large clean fleshly colored hand with beautiful long fingernails that placed into the inner chambers of the earth.<br><br>
As I walked along long and narrow corridors, I could hear screams off in the distance. Curious, I approached and then all of a sudden I saw mankind, individually imprisoned in little 3-4 feet by 6 feet cells. All of them were bound in chains and tormented by a fire that did not consume but tore at their souls with gnashing and great horror of horrors. The sizzling flames burned them deeply from within. As if it was their souls, that suffered the most.<br>
Their screams were indescribable, I could not believe that a man could scream with such agony and pain.<br><br>
WHY! WHY! WHY!!! DIDN'T,  I  LISTEN,&quot; were the cries, of all those imprisoned and shackled and tortured with great pain. Like you Art, I felt completely powerless. Yet, what was evident to me was the absence of repentance, as if such a thing no longer existed.<br><br>
Each time today, when I see a crime, when I hear of those that do wrong and avoid Justice I remember that dream/vision and feel completely helpless all over again, absent is repentance.<br>

